:"1355","about 1358":"okolo 1358","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Gwernvale, Llangatwg, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangattock, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1358–":"omkring 1358–Afdød","1350–Male":"1350–Afdød","1355–Male":"1355–Afdød","1356–Male":"1356–Afdød","1358–Male":"1358–Afdød","1360–Female":"1360–Afdød","1340–1395":"1340–1395","–Male":"Afdød","1336–Male":"1336–Afdød","1330–Female":"1330–Afdød","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","about 1358":"omkring 1358","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Gwernvale, Llangatwg, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangattock, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1358–":"circa 1358–Overleden","1350–Male":"1350–Overleden","1355–Male":"1355–Overleden","1356–Male":"1356–Overleden","1358–Male":"1358–Overleden","1360–Female":"1360–Overleden","1340–1395":"1340–1395","–Male":"Overleden","1336–Male":"1336–Overleden","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","about 1358":"circa 1358","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Gwernvale, Llangatwg, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangattock, Breconshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1358–":"about 1358–Deceased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","1358–Male":"1358–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1340–1395":"1340–1395","–Male":"Deceased","1336–Male":"1336–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","about 1358":"about 1358","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Gwernvale, Llangatwg, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangattock, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert ap Seisyll was born about 1358, in Llangattock, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Seisyll, was 23 and his mother, Seisyll, was 30. He had at least 2 sons with Siesyll."},"et":{"about 1358–":"umbes 1358–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1358–Male":"1358–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1340–1395":"1340–1395","–Male":"Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","about 1358":"umbes 1358","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Gwernvale, Llangatwg, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangattock, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1358–":"noin 1358–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1356–Male":"1356–Kuollut","1358–Male":"1358–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1340–1395":"1340–1395","–Male":"Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1336":"1336","1358":"1358","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","about 1358":"noin 1358","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","Gwernvale, Llang